  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT72-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">talaimakaṉ taṉ vēṟupāṭu kaṇṭu viṉāya pāṅkaṟku uraittatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Declared by HIM to the companion who had questioned [him] when seeing changes in him.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT72">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                pūvot talamarun takaiya vēvot</l>
<l>                tellāru maṟiya nōycey taṉavē</l>
<l>                tēmoḻit tiraṇṭa meṉṟōṇ māmalaip</l>
<l>                parīi vittiya vēṉaṟ</l>
<l>                kurīi yōppuvāḷ perumaḻaik kaṇṇē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent">Like flowers, like arrows that are fit to flit,</l>
          <l>they have caused pain
            <choice>
                <seg>for all to know,</seg>
                <seg>known by all people<note place="foot">That is, not his personal situation, but referring to love-pain as such.</note></seg>
            </choice>
          </l>
          <l>the big rain eyes of her who chases birds away</l>
          <l rend="indent">
            <choice>
            <seg>from the millet into which cotton is sown</seg>
            <seg>away from cotton sown<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">vittiya-v-ēṉal: ēṉal</term> "millet" reads Cām., and this praxis of doubly sowing a field seems also to be found in KT 82 (beans and millet). As for the wording, it seems equally well possible to read <term xml:lang="ta">vēṉal</term> "summer" (4b), but arguably cotton is in less danger of being eaten away by birds than millet, which in any case is the topos.</note> in summer</seg>
          </choice>
            on the big mountain,
          
          </l>
          <l rend="indent">[she with] honey[-sweet] words [and] round tender shoulders.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
